******
[1] South Carolina
Date: Tue 13 Aug 2013
Source: Independent Mail [edited]
http://www.independentmail.com/news/2013/aug/13/encephalitis-cases-rising-sc/


Eastern equine encephalitis cases are increasing in South Carolina. The mosquitoborne disease, which can cause twitching, paralysis, depression, and death, has turned up in 25 horses across the state so far this year [2013], according to Dr Boyd Parr, state veterinarian and director of Clemson University Livestock Poultry Health. 7 new cases have been reported in the last week.

"These diagnoses are a vivid reminder of the threat that mosquitoborne diseases represent to horses in our state," Parr said. "Maintaining protection by vaccinating horses is very important this year." Infected mosquitoes that feed on both birds and mammals can transmit the disease to horses and humans. 9 of every 10 horses infected with the virus die of the disease. Any livestock (including horses) that display neurologic signs (stumbling, circling, head pressing, depression, or apprehension) must be reported to the state veterinarian at 803-788-2260 within 48 hours, according to the state law.

The Upstate [western South Carolina] has, thus far, avoided any cases of eastern equine encephalitis (EEE) or West Nile virus (WNV); in fact, there have been no reported West Nile cases in the state this year [2013]. State officials watch each disease closely, as they can be transmitted to humans. There were 14 confirmed cases of encephalitis and 7 of West Nile in the state last year.

Total confirmed encephalitis cases as of 9 Aug 2013 were Horry County (10), Charleston County (3), Sumter County (3), Marion County (2), and one each in Barnwell, Berkeley, Clarendon, Colleton, Lee, and Williamsburg counties [adds up to 24, not 25. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ]. Weekly updates are posted at Clemson Livestock Poultry Health's Facebook page.

Eastern equine encephalitis is preventable by vaccinating horses. State officials advise horse owners to make sure both encephalitis and West Nile vaccinations are up-to-date.

